{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/calm_accountability_direction.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Design Direction: calm_accountability_direction\n## Target Emotion\n- First 10 seconds: grounded and in-control, with immediate clarity about today’s wake commitment.\n- Wake state: focused urgency without panic; one clear action and no visual noise.\n- After task completion: respected and steady; accountability is framed as continuity, not judgment.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Layout density: medium-compact on home/list, low-density on active wake/completion to reduce decision load.\n- Contrast model: neutral surfaces with strong text contrast; urgency is signaled by hierarchy and state labels, not aggressive color floods.\n- Component shape language: iOS-native rounded rectangles and segmented groupings; avoid novelty containers that weaken scanning.\n- Information hierarchy: one primary CTA per screen, one supporting status line, secondary actions visually demoted.\n- Empty-state tone: instructional and calm (\"here is the next step\"), never guilt-coded.\n- Native iOS alignment: SF Symbols, large-title/list conventions, system sheets, standard tab behavior, predictable back/close affordances.\n\n## Colors And Tokens\n- Semantic tokens:\n  - `color.bg.primary`, `color.bg.secondary`, `color.surface.card`\n  - `color.text.primary`, `color.text.secondary`, `color.text.muted`\n  - `color.action.primary`, `color.action.primaryPressed`, `color.action.secondary`\n  - `color.state.success`, `color.state.warning`, `color.state.destructive`, `color.state.disabled`\n  - `color.state.focusRing`, `color.state.highContrastBorder`\n- Light/dark behavior: hue-consistent tokens with luminance remapping per mode; do not swap semantic meaning between modes.\n- Accent strategy: single calm accent (blue-green family) reserved for commitment actions and progress confirmations.\n- Destructive states: red only for irreversible outcomes (delete task/account), not for missed wake messaging.\n- Success states: green for completion confirmation and repair completion; never accompanied by confetti/gamified pressure.\n- Disabled states: opacity + contrast-safe text fallback, not opacity alone.\n- High-contrast fallback: explicit border and text token overrides for WCAG-safe separations on cards/chips.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all text styles scale using semantic styles; no fixed-size text in action-critical surfaces.\n- Roles:\n  - Title: `.largeTitle`/`.title2` for wake intent and active-task headline.\n  - Body: `.body` for instructions and status.\n  - Caption/meta: `.footnote` for timing/context labels.\n- Numeric treatment: tabular numerals for timers, streak counts, and completion history values.\n- Minimum readable sizes: body-equivalent minimum 17pt in wake-critical areas; footnote never below 13pt equivalent.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: quick orientation transitions, minimal decorative movement, clear state-change feedback.\n- Reduce Motion: replace scale/slide transitions with crossfade and static state swaps.\n- Haptics: soft impact on start/complete; warning haptic only for explicit failure states.\n- Timing ranges: 120-180ms tap feedback, 220-320ms state transitions, 0ms when Reduce Motion requires it.\n- Wake-state restraint: no looping attention animations during active wake; only one-time state acknowledgment.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: 3-step progressive setup (intent, default schedule, optional strictness) with visible skip-safe path and reversible defaults.\n- Home: top module is \"Next Wake Commitment\" with single primary action; metrics and history preview are secondary.\n- Primary list: group tasks by readiness (`Tonight`, `Later`, `Paused`), with clear status chips and low-friction resume.\n- Create/edit: sequence as `Intent -> Timing -> Safeguards -> Review`; avoid dumping advanced controls on first pane.\n- Active task: full focus surface with one dominant CTA, current-state banner, and a plainly labeled fallback action.\n- Completion: immediate confirmation, one suggested next step (log reflection or set next wake), plus optional repair guidance.\n- History/streaks: show reliability trend + \"why changed\" annotations; include one-tap repair planning after misses.\n- Profile/settings: separate Mission Controls, Account/Billing, and Help/Legal into distinct sections with different visual weight.\n- Paywall/subscription: premium framed as reliability tools and deeper insights, surfaced contextually after value moments, never blocking urgent wake flows.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise: stronger accountability tooling (advanced safeguards, deeper history insights, adaptive planning).\n- Must remain free: core wake flow, basic task creation/editing, completion logging, and non-coercive recovery actions.\n- Dark-pattern avoidance: no countdown pressure, forced trial walls in wake flow, deceptive close buttons, or shaming upsell copy.\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: risk of ambiguous status chips and action labels; require explicit state announcements and action verbs.\n- Dynamic Type: risk of clipped cards in home/list; enforce multiline-safe layouts and vertical growth.\n- Contrast: muted neutral palettes can underperform; require token-level contrast audits in both modes.\n- Reduced motion: animation-heavy progress transitions may confuse; provide clear non-motion state labels.\n- Haptics-only feedback: never rely on haptics as sole completion/failure signal.\n- Cognitive load: too many safeguards in active wake can create paralysis; progressive disclosure is required.\n- One-handed use: top-heavy controls in large phones can reduce completion reliability; keep primary wake CTA thumb-reachable.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: tokenized theming + stateful wake surfaces can fragment if not centralized in a design-token layer.\n- Custom component risk: bespoke status chips/commitment cards may diverge from iOS behavior; keep wrappers around native primitives.\n- Animation risk: state transitions across active/completion/history can create race conditions with async task updates.\n- App Store risk: if paywall intrudes on core alarm/wake utility, review risk increases for deceptive gating.\n- Localization risk: calm microcopy may expand significantly in some languages; design for multiline and variable button widths.\n- Scope tradeoff: full reliability annotations in history may require backend/event model changes; phase rollout by surface.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md` - consolidated constraints, top-screen opportunities, and anti-patterns.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md` - competitor flow principles for sequencing and urgent-mode focus.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md` - pattern evidence for progressive onboarding and single-action active states.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` - source-limited pattern guidance emphasizing adaptation-not-copy.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md` - platform-aligned accessibility/interruption constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md` - calm vs urgent behavioral tone separation.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md` - hypothesis-only pain framing and evidence caution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json` - environment and evidence limitations affecting confidence.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json` - confirms earlier evidence gaps and why conservative inference is necessary.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive setup with reversible defaults and explicit next-step framing.\n- Single-primary-action wake execution with persistent state clarity.\n- Recovery-first accountability language after misses.\n- Clear separation between mission-critical controls and account/legal surfaces.\n- Reliability explanations (why streak changed) over pure streak gamification.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Exact competitor, Mobbin, or PageFlows visual compositions, spacing systems, copy, iconography, or motion signatures.\n- Proprietary brand palettes, badges, reward metaphors, or onboarding scripts.\n- Punitive/shame-driven wake recovery patterns and coercive monetization sequences.\n- Any undocumented external claims presented as validated facts in this run.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- No credentials, tokens, private links, signed URLs, cookies, API keys, or user secrets were used or reproduced.\n- If encountered in source material: secret material omitted.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/hard_wake_direction.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Design Direction: hard_wake_direction\n## Target Emotion\n- First 10 seconds: immediate urgency with control, like a safety checklist before takeoff.\n- Wake state: high accountability, minimal ambiguity, no decorative distraction.\n- After task completion: decompression and relief, then clear next-step confidence.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Layout density: compact in wake-critical surfaces, standard spacing elsewhere.\n- Contrast model: high-contrast foreground for active wake surfaces, neutral system surfaces for setup/history.\n- Shape language: squared cards (10-12pt radius), strong edge definition, prominent primary action container.\n- Information hierarchy: one dominant CTA, one state banner, one consequence line; everything else demoted.\n- Empty-state tone: operational and direct (\"No wake task armed\" + immediate next action), never playful.\n- Native iOS fit: SF Symbols, iOS sheet/navigation patterns, standard tab bar and large-title collapse behavior.\n\n## Colors And Tokens\n- Semantic tokens:\n  - `wake.bg.primary`\n  - `wake.bg.urgent`\n  - `wake.fg.primary`\n  - `wake.fg.muted`\n  - `wake.action.primary`\n  - `wake.action.destructive`\n  - `wake.state.success`\n  - `wake.state.warning`\n  - `wake.state.disabled`\n  - `wake.border.strong`\n- Light mode: `wake.bg.primary` near-white; `wake.bg.urgent` warm off-red tint; text remains near-black.\n- Dark mode: `wake.bg.primary` near-black; `wake.bg.urgent` deep red-brown tint; text near-white.\n- Accent strategy: single alert accent for wake-critical controls, blue reserved for non-urgent navigation actions.\n- Destructive states: red foreground + icon + explicit text label, never color-only signaling.\n- Success states: muted green confirmation surfaces with short factual copy (no confetti treatment).\n- Disabled states: lowered contrast plus explicit reason text under the control.\n- High-contrast fallback: swap to system semantic colors (`.label`, `.systemBackground`, `.systemRed`) and add 1px borders on key controls.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all mission-critical text scales through AX sizes; CTA containers grow vertically instead of truncating.\n- Roles:\n  - Title: wake status and phase label.\n  - Body: instructions and consequence text.\n  - Caption: timing detail and audit metadata.\n- Numeric treatment: tabular figures for countdowns, streak counts, and completion timestamps.\n- Minimum readable sizes: 17pt body baseline, 15pt secondary metadata, never below 13pt for tappable-context labels.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: quick, directional, state-explaining transitions (arm -> active -> complete), not ornamental movement.\n- Reduce Motion: replace transforms with opacity swaps and static state banners.\n- Haptics: single medium impact on wake start, success notification on completion, warning notification on miss.\n- Timing ranges: 120-180ms micro state change, 220-320ms screen transition; avoid chained animations.\n- Wake-state restraint: suppress non-essential animation while task is active to reduce cognitive load.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: 3-step max; step 1 defines wake intent, step 2 sets minimum viable schedule, step 3 confirms. Skip-safe path allowed with default schedule and later edit.\n- Home: top module is \"Next Wake Mission\" with hard state label (`Armed`, `Due`, `Missed`, `Recovered`) and one primary action.\n- Primary list: tasks sorted by urgency first, then recency; each row shows state token and next trigger time.\n- Create/edit: progressive disclosure. Required fields first; advanced constraints hidden under \"Strict Options\".\n- Active task: full focus surface with one primary action, one fallback action, and persistent consequence/status line.\n- Completion: immediate factual summary (time, streak effect, next wake), then recovery options if partially failed.\n- History/streaks: emphasize reliability trend and miss-repair actions over badge collection.\n- Profile/settings: split sections into `Wake Operations`, `Preferences`, `Account & Legal`; dangerous actions isolated at bottom.\n- Paywall/subscription: shown after value proof moments (post-completion/history insight), never interrupting an active wake flow.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise: higher reliability tooling (advanced schedule rules, deeper reliability analytics, smart recovery suggestions).\n- Remain free: core wake/task loop (create, arm, complete, basic history, basic reminders).\n- Dark-pattern avoidance: no countdown pressure on paywall, no fake scarcity, no blocking dismissal during wake-critical paths.\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: dense wake UI can become verbose; custom rotor labels are needed for state, timer, and primary action.\n- Dynamic Type: compact urgent layout may clip metadata if component heights are fixed.\n- Contrast: urgent tints can reduce legibility in dark mode if red overlays are too saturated.\n- Reduced motion: state clarity may collapse if motion is removed without explicit textual transitions.\n- Haptics-only feedback: misses users with haptics disabled; all haptic events need mirrored visual/text feedback.\n- Cognitive load: hard-accountability tone can overwhelm if multiple warnings stack in active state.\n- One-handed use: top-heavy controls conflict with reachability; primary wake action should anchor in lower thumb zone.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: custom token system + multi-state surfaces can fragment modifiers and increase regressions.\n- Custom component risk: reusable \"Wake State Banner\" and \"Urgent Action Card\" may require careful environment-driven theming.\n- Animation risk: state machine bugs likely if wake transitions are modeled ad hoc instead of explicit enum-driven flow.\n- App Store risk: over-aggressive urgency language or alarm-like coercion could be flagged as manipulative UX.\n- Localization risk: compact hard-tone copy may expand significantly in non-English locales and break hierarchy.\n- Scope tradeoffs: if time-constrained, prioritize active-task clarity and history explanations before visual polish.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md`: consolidated weaknesses/opportunities and evidence constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`: onboarding, tab clarity, urgent active-task pattern signals.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`: evidence-gap handling and onboarding friction caution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`: fallback principles for calm setup, urgent execution, recovery.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`: progressive onboarding and single-action urgent flow heuristics.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`: iOS-native accessibility and predictability constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`: tone separation between setup and urgent execution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`: environment/network limits affecting evidence confidence.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`: confirms prior research gaps and live-research dependency.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive disclosure for setup: intent first, strictness later.\n- Single dominant action during wake-critical moments.\n- Explicit state language (`Armed`, `Due`, `Missed`, `Recovered`) across home, active, and history.\n- Recovery-first completion framing with immediate retry/repair options.\n- Strong separation of mission-critical controls from account/legal settings.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Any competitor or library-specific layout composition, spacing blueprint, or visual motif.\n- Any proprietary screenshots, icon packs, brand palettes, or marketing copy.\n- Any distinctive gamification sequence, badge art, or celebratory animation cadence from third-party apps.\n- Any coercive monetization sequence that interrupts urgent wake execution.\n- Any unverified claims presented as factual review insights when evidence is source-limited.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- secret material omitted\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/gamified_streak_direction.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Design Direction: gamified_streak_direction\n## Target Emotion\n- First 10 seconds: immediate momentum, like “I can secure today’s streak in one action.”\n- Wake state: focused urgency without panic; user should feel challenged but never punished.\n- After task completion: earned progress and continuity, with a clear next micro-goal to return tomorrow.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Layout density: medium on home/history (to show streak context), low on active wake (single dominant action).\n- Contrast model: neutral surfaces with high-contrast semantic accents only on streak-critical states.\n- Shape language: rounded-rect cards and circular progress marks; keep iOS-native control chrome.\n- Information hierarchy: 1) today status, 2) next action, 3) streak context, 4) secondary controls.\n- Empty-state tone: “start your streak loop” coaching, not guilt for missing history.\n- iOS nativeness: SF Symbols, standard tab bar/nav patterns, native sheets, native toggles/segmented controls.\n\n## Colors And Tokens\n- Core semantic tokens:\n  - `color.bg.primary`, `color.bg.secondary`, `color.surface.card`\n  - `color.text.primary`, `color.text.secondary`, `color.text.inverse`\n  - `color.streak.active`, `color.streak.frozen`, `color.streak.missed`\n  - `color.state.success`, `color.state.warning`, `color.state.destructive`, `color.state.disabled`\n  - `color.cta.primary`, `color.cta.primaryPressed`, `color.cta.secondary`\n- Light/dark behavior: preserve hue identity for streak states across modes; adjust luminance only.\n- Accent strategy: one streak accent family for progress moments; avoid multi-accent noise during wake flow.\n- Destructive states: reserve red only for truly destructive account/task actions, not missed-day messaging.\n- Success states: use green for completion confirmation, then transition to streak accent for continuity.\n- Disabled states: desaturate + lower contrast but keep WCAG-readable labels.\n- High-contrast fallback: replace subtle fills with 2px semantic outlines and stronger text contrast pairings.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all streak counters, CTA labels, and state banners scale with `UIFontMetrics`; no clipped numeric badges.\n- Roles:\n  - Title: wake status + streak headline (`Title2`/`Title3` equivalent)\n  - Body: instructions and recovery text (`Body`)\n  - Caption: metadata like “last 7 days” (`Caption1` minimum)\n- Numeric treatment: tabular figures for countdowns/streak numbers to prevent width-jump flicker.\n- Minimum readable sizes: 17pt body baseline; captions never below 12pt at default and must scale upward.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: motion confirms state change (armed -> active -> completed), never decorative-only.\n- Reduce Motion: replace scale/spring with opacity and color transitions; disable streak confetti.\n- Haptics:\n  - success haptic on completion\n  - warning haptic on miss-risk reminders\n  - no repeated haptic loops in wake-critical countdowns\n- Timing ranges: 140-220ms for tap confirmations; 220-320ms for screen/state transitions.\n- Wake-state restraint: one animated focal element max on active-task screen.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: frame streak loop in 3 steps (intent -> wake challenge style -> recovery promise), with skip-safe defaults.\n- Home: top card is “Today’s streak mission”; secondary modules (history/profile shortcuts) move below fold.\n- Primary list: tasks sorted by streak impact (today due, at risk, backlog) rather than creation date alone.\n- Create/edit: include “streak difficulty” and “miss recovery mode” settings with plain-language preview.\n- Active task: single dominant CTA, visible progress ring, explicit next-state label (“1 step left to lock streak”).\n- Completion: immediate success confirmation + “protect tomorrow” action; no shame copy for near misses.\n- History/streaks: show streak timeline with reason codes (completed/missed/recovered) and one-tap repair guidance.\n- Profile/settings: split into `Account`, `Wake Preferences`, `Streak Rules`, `Support/Legal`; isolate destructive actions.\n- Paywall/subscription: premium upsell on advanced analytics/long-range streak insights, never blocking wake completion.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise this supports: deeper streak intelligence (patterns, risk forecasting, advanced recovery planning).\n- Remains free: core wake task execution, basic streak tracking, and standard recovery path.\n- Avoid dark patterns:\n  - no false urgency countdowns tied to purchase\n  - no paywall interstitial during active wake flow\n  - no withholding missed-day explanations behind premium\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: streak rings and badges risk unlabeled semantics; must announce state + consequence.\n- Dynamic Type: dense history chips can truncate at larger sizes; require wrapping/reflow.\n- Contrast: accent-on-tint streak chips can fail in dark mode without high-contrast fallback.\n- Reduced motion: confetti/progress pulses can overwhelm; provide static alternatives.\n- Haptics-only feedback: never rely on haptics alone for completion/miss signals.\n- Cognitive load: gamification can over-clutter home; enforce strict priority stack.\n- One-handed use: primary wake CTA must sit in lower-thumb reach zone on common iPhone sizes.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: custom streak timeline + progress ring states can create view-state explosion.\n- Custom component risk: over-custom badges/rings may diverge from design system and accessibility defaults.\n- Animation risk: combined timers, haptics, and transitions can produce jank under low-power conditions.\n- App Store risk: aggressive gamification language could be interpreted as manipulative if recovery is punitive.\n- Localization risk: short English streak labels may overflow in longer locales; plan tokenized, testable variants.\n- Scope tradeoffs: prioritize wake-state clarity and history reason-codes before advanced reward cosmetics.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md` - consolidated weakness/pattern constraints and anti-patterns.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md` - current IA, screen inventory, and known UX weaknesses in WakeTask.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md` - evidence for cancellable onboarding, focused active-task surface, and settings separation.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md` - evidence for progressive setup, single-action urgency, and readable streak accountability.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` - source-limited fallback patterns for calm setup, urgent execution, and recovery-first behavior.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md` - accessibility/discoverability and interruption-safe constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md` - emotional tone split between low-pressure setup and high-pressure wake moments.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json` - evidence that external sources were network-limited, requiring conservative inference.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md` - explicit reminder that review claims are provisional and must avoid fabricated certainty.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive onboarding with reversible defaults and explicit progress.\n- Single-primary-action active wake flow with clear next-state language.\n- Recovery-first completion and missed-day messaging.\n- Streak history explainability with reason-coded outcomes.\n- Clear separation of mission controls from account/legal/settings surfaces.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Exact competitor/page library layouts, spacing systems, icon sets, reward badges, or copy.\n- Proprietary motion signatures or distinctive screen-to-screen choreography sequences.\n- Punitive, shame-based, or coercive monetization tied to wake urgency.\n- Any unverified App Store claim presented as factual product evidence.\n\n## No Secret Output\nNo credentials, tokens, cookies, signed URLs, private links, API keys, or other secrets were included.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
