{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/cross-critique.md <<'EOF'\n# Design Cross Critique\n## Direction Coverage\n- Reviewed directions in \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/`:\n- `calm_accountability_direction`\n- `hard_wake_direction`\n- `gamified_streak_direction`\n- Cross-critique evaluates each role against each reviewed direction.\n\n## Half-Asleep Usability Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Strong recognition speed from single-primary-action framing and low-noise active state. Risk: medium-compact home/list density can still overload tired users if chip vocabulary is not aggressively simplified.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Best raw urgency clarity (`Armed/Due/Missed/Recovered`) and explicit consequence line helps error recovery. Risk: checklist tone plus compact wake surfaces can feel cognitively heavy when groggy; warning stacking could slow task start.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Good momentum framing and clear “today mission” hierarchy. Risk: streak context and progress ring add interpretation overhead; tired users may parse “game state” before core action.\n\n## Premium iOS Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Most aligned with iOS restraint, semantic tokenization, standard nav/sheets, and non-gimmicky motion. Risk: custom status chips and commitment cards must stay wrapper-level over native controls.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Native patterns are mostly respected, but squared/strong-edge visual language may read less platform-organic if overdone. Risk: red-tinted urgent surfaces can look alarmist or non-systemic in dark mode.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Keeps native chrome but introduces higher custom visual identity (rings, streak chips, reward framing). Risk: easiest path to “webby gamification layer on top of iOS” if typography and spacing discipline slips.\n\n## Conversion Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Credible premium story (reliability insights/safeguards) without coercion; good post-value upsell timing. Risk: may undersell emotional payoff versus more aspirational competitors.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Premium promise around serious reliability tools is clear and differentiated for high-intent users. Risk: hard tone can reduce affinity and trial conversion for users who want support rather than pressure.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Strongest perceived value narrative for ongoing engagement and analytics upsell moments. Risk: if miss-recovery feels punitive, it can look manipulative and hurt trust.\n\n## Accessibility Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Good foundations (Dynamic Type intent, reduced-motion path, non-haptic-only policy). Risk: muted palette and dense status chips could fail contrast/VoiceOver semantics if not rigorously audited.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Explicit textual states are good for non-visual understanding. Risk: compact layouts under AX sizes and urgent tint contrast in dark mode are high-risk failure points.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Explicitly acknowledges reduced motion and haptic alternatives. Risk: rings/badges/history chips are semantically fragile; must not depend on color/animation to communicate streak state.\n\n## Anti-Clone Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Safest from clone risk; pattern adaptation is generic and operational, not stylistically derivative. Main risk is converging on familiar productivity-card compositions.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Also relatively safe if tone/copy stays product-specific. Risk comes from overly recognizable “alarm challenge” visual framing if urgency modules mirror known competitors too closely.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Highest clone exposure due to common streak metaphors, rings, and mission language seen across habit apps. Needs deliberate originality in copy system, icon semantics, and timeline rendering.\n\n## Implementation Risk Critic\n- `calm_accountability_direction`: Lowest implementation risk of the three; mostly disciplined IA/hierarchy and token work. Risks are manageable if history “why changed” annotations are phased.\n- `hard_wake_direction`: Medium risk; requires robust state machine, strict tone consistency, and careful urgent-surface QA across themes/locales.\n- `gamified_streak_direction`: Highest risk; custom timeline/rings plus multi-state gamification logic increase SwiftUI state complexity, animation/haptics coordination burden, and screenshot test matrix size.\n\n## Scorecard Inputs\n- `calm_accountability_direction`\n- `differentiation`: Moderate; differentiated by calm accountability tone more than novel visuals.\n- `native_ios_quality`: High; strongest restraint and HIG alignment potential.\n- `wake_state_usability`: High; clear single-action model, low panic, good recovery framing.\n- `conversion_potential`: Moderate-high; trust-positive, but less emotionally “exciting.”\n- `accessibility`: High potential with chip semantics/contrast audits completed.\n- `implementation_risk`: Low-medium; token and annotation scope are the main risks.\n- `visual_distinctiveness`: Moderate; risks feeling safe/expected without stronger brand cues.\n\n- `hard_wake_direction`\n- `differentiation`: Moderate-high; explicit operational accountability stance is distinct.\n- `native_ios_quality`: Medium-high; mostly native, but hard-edged urgency aesthetic can drift off-platform.\n- `wake_state_usability`: High for decisive users; medium for exhausted users sensitive to cognitive pressure.\n- `conversion_potential`: Moderate; compelling for serious users, potentially alienating for broader audience.\n- `accessibility`: Medium; compact density + urgent color handling are meaningful hazards.\n- `implementation_risk`: Medium; state architecture and tone QA are core risk drivers.\n- `visual_distinctiveness`: Moderate-high; clearer personality than calm direction.\n\n- `gamified_streak_direction`\n- `differentiation`: High; strongest thematic identity via streak system.\n- `native_ios_quality`: Medium; native scaffolding present, but custom gamified layer can degrade polish.\n- `wake_state_usability`: Medium; good active-task focus but added gamified semantics increase tired-user parsing cost.\n- `conversion_potential`: High upside; clear premium analytics narrative and retention hooks.\n- `accessibility`: Medium; ring/chip semantics and color dependence need strong remediation.\n- `implementation_risk`: High; custom components and state interactions significantly raise delivery risk.\n- `visual_distinctiveness`: High; most visually ownable if executed with restraint.\n\n## Consensus Recommendations\n- Role-specific recommendation: Half-asleep usability and Premium iOS critics favor `calm_accountability_direction` as the safest core for wake-critical UX.\n- Role-specific recommendation: Conversion critic favors borrowing selected momentum framing from `gamified_streak_direction` (post-completion/history surfaces only, not active wake).\n- Role-specific recommendation: Implementation risk critic recommends avoiding full `gamified_streak_direction` scope in first release slice.\n- Role-specific recommendation: Accessibility critic requires hard acceptance criteria before approving `hard_wake_direction` or `gamified_streak_direction` (AX text expansion, contrast, VoiceOver semantics on status artifacts).\n- Integration suggestion for tournament scoring: treat `calm_accountability_direction` as baseline architecture, then A/B limited motivational overlays from `gamified_streak_direction` outside urgent wake flow.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- No credentials, tokens, private links, signed URLs, cookies, API keys, or user secrets are included.\n- If encountered in source material: secret material omitted.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
